Two cents, we have had revolutions even in this Generation of AI, first came CNNs, RNNs and then Transformers. So there is some likelihood that there will new type of models too, that will allow smaller more compact models. This was true earlier too, when ANN flourished they then got replaced by SVMs. US puts lots of money both in academic research of flavours and Industry taking bets in those (DeepMind:RL, OpenAI:CNN/Transformers, AllenAI, Vicarious:Prob models, Ayasdi: Topological models etc) and so on. If we want to be ahead, we as an ecosystems will have to take those calculated risks I feel. We probably should work on what the next models could be, not just trying to reach parity.
Yup absolutely agree .. there is too much fixation on existing Models. For eg, I would like to understand how Multi-modal FMs will evolve in the coming years.

I am wondering if there is any customer/investor interest in AI Ops products these days.  Anyone here investing or building in this area?
https://signal.nfx.com/investor-lists/top-ai-seed-investors
Hi Ankesh ... Im looking to invest in AI middleware companies.. [EMAIL]
I meant the parallels of dynatrace/ moogsoft/ bigpanda

I'm sure there are several investors looking at this category so, for the right team, there should be plenty of interest. I've been looking at MLops startups across India and US since 2017 but frankly it's a tough area with plenty of OSS tools and no big success after a decade of trying. From Michelangelo to fblearner to airflow to various cloud native tools and 100s more, the MLOps category unfortunately got too fragmented based on different tastes of different data science teams. What's interesting about LLMops is that it seems to be much closer and integrated to the enterprise data stack today than ML ever was -- and therefore likely to align to more standardized practices -- so I'm more hopeful for this category. We've made one adjacent investment here at lightspeed and happy to see more.
That‚Äôs a nice observation
related: is there an open-source tool that is close to fblearner?

Sorry for the confusion, I understand the term AI Ops can be confused with ML Ops which is more popularly known. AI Ops was a term coined by Gartner to categorise the capability of using AI in the IT Ops or Devops realm(like for incident detection, fault localisation, etc) whereas ML Ops is the domain of Operating ML workloads.
Some example companies playing in the AI Ops domain are moogsoft, bigpanda, dynatrace, datadog, servicenow
Fblearner is nothing but a feature store and facebook scale. Every company has a feature store nowadays.
I meant the whole model lifecycle management (particularly cloning flows, click to start training job, model lineage, data selection). I know mlflow does some of this but it seems very barebones.
Databricks enterprise version has whole of it since 2020, we used it actively at my previous company

Profound. "In some of our earliest work to leverage AI and ML ‚Äî such as delivering the most relevant content to each person ‚Äî we noticed that the *largest improvements in accuracy* often came from quick experiments, feature engineering, and model tuning rather than applying fundamentally different algorithms"
https://engineering.fb.com/2016/05/09/core-data/introducing-fblearner-flow-facebook-s-ai-backbone/
‚ÄéPOLL:

2c: We had used DVC and datalad at different times. Datalad is great if you use git-annex, it is great for data provence, model tracking etc but no flows, atleast that is my memory. One click etc were mostly thin layers on top. Automated gsheets sheets (basically touch a particular cell and an experiment is automatically run on cloud). Over time we figured out Excel sheets were best for our usecase, this is about about 20+ projects + upto few 1000 experiments per project. Excel sheet was great because we could pivot on important characteristics etc. We sort of had the feel of what Quora described about their CI/CD deployment, people doing all sorts of experiments now that it was super easy to do. DVC also supports basic flows etc. Don't know enough about details FBlearner's  flows to compare.
Would love to hear what others use.
AB testing everything is the reason meta products have no taste (personal opinion)
